# Store JSX in Variables

When conditions become complex, you can store JSX in variables and then render that variable.

```jsx
let button;
if (isLoggedIn) {
  button = <LogoutButton />;
} else {
  button = <LoginButton />;
}

return <div>{button}</div>;
```

This keeps the JSX return clean and moves logic above.

slides.codeSnippet:
function Message({ status }) {
  let message;
  if (status === 'success') {
    message = <p className="success">Operation successful!</p>;
  } else if (status === 'error') {
    message = <p className="error">Something went wrong.</p>;
  } else {
    message = <p>Processing...</p>;
  }

  return <div>{message}</div>;
}

